Totally, 947 samples were detected by RT-RAA and qRT-PCR (Table 2
) (Supplementary Table S2). Among the 947 samples, RT-RAA results of 926 samples were consistent with qRT-PCR (330 were positive, 596 were negative) and 21 samples (1 sputum and 20 pharynx swabs) were inconsistent. The total coincidence rate between RT-RAA and qRT-PCR was 100% in both group A and B. The Ct value of positive samples was in the range of 17.00 to 37.00 in group A and 20.50 to 36.50 in group B. In group C, 6 samples had inconsistent results. Among them, 2 samples with Ct value of 38.00 were positive by qRT-PCR but missed by RT-RAA, the remaining 4 samples were negative by qRT-PCR but positive by RT-RAA. In group D, 15 samples had discordant results including 6 samples positive by qRT-PCR but missed by RT-RAA and the Ct values of these samples were 38.33, 38.22, 39.07, 36.89, 37.56 and 38.16, respectively. The remaining 9 samples were negative by qRT-PCR but positive by RT-RAA. Positive rates of RT-RAA and qRT-PCR in different sample types are shown in Table 3
. The lower respiratory tract samples (bronchoalveolar lavage fluid) had the highest positive rate, followed by nasopharyngeal swab, nasal swab and pharynx swab. Compared with qRT-PCR, the sensitivity of RT-RAA was 97.63% and the specificity was 97.87%. The positive predictive value (PPV) was 96.21% (330/343) (95% CI: 93.45 to 97.88), the negative predictive value (NPV) was 98.68% (596/604) (95% CI: 97.30 to 99.38) and the total coincidence rate was 97.78% (926/947) (95% CI: 96.80 to 98.70), the Kappa was 0.952 (P < 0.05).
